ontinue to circulate in Malawi. At the heart of the book is Ashforth’s desire to understand how claims to truth, the pursuit of justice, and demands for security work in contemporary Africa, where stories of witchcraft can be terrifying. Guiding us through the history of legal customs and their interactions with the court of public opinion, Ashforth asks challenging questions about responsibility, occult forces, and the imperfect but vital mechanisms of law. A beautifully written and provocative book, The Trials of Mrs. K. will be an essential text for understanding what justice means in a fragile and dangerous world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aTrials (Witchcraft)zMalawi. 0aTrials (Witchcraft)-Malawi. 0aWitchcraftxSocial aspectszMalawi. 0aWitchcraft-Social aspects-Malawi. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ajustice, legal system, witches, spooky, belief, folklore, magic, magical, mythology, african studies, afroamerican, malwai, africa, hospital, witchcraft, rumors, doxing, harassment, bullying, social, psychological, true story, contemporary, modern, real world, customs, public opinion, court, jury, judge, punishment, crime, occult, controversial, dangerous, sexism, society, community, bias, academic, scholarly, learning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226322537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226322537/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles